# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hierarchical-edge-bundling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] A **chord diagram** is a graphical method of displaying the inter-relationships between data in a matrix.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The data are arranged radially around a circle with the relationships between the data points typically drawn as arcs connecting the data.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The format can be aesthetically pleasing, making it a popular choice in the world of data visualization.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The primary use of chord diagrams is to show the flows or connections between several entities (called nodes).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Each entity is represented by a fragment (often colored or pattered) along the circumference of the circle.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Arcs are drawn between entities to show flows (and exchanges in economics).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The thickness of the arc is proportional to the significance of the flow.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Chord diagrams get their name from terminology used in geometry.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] A chord of a circle is a geometric line segment whose endpoints both lie on the circle.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Chord diagrams are also known as **radial network diagrams** and may sometimes be referred to as a type of circular layout.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] While a small amount of data could be represented in a circular diagram using straight lines to show the interconnections, a diagram featuring numerous lines would quickly become illegible.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] To reduce the visual complexity, chord diagrams employ a technique called hierarchical edge bundling.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Chord diagrams are useful for showing relationships between entities and their relative magnitudes in comparison to alternative arcs.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] As a result, chord diagrams are popular in migration studies, economic flows, and genome studies.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/chord-diagram-information-visualization] They have also been used to highlight unexplored relationships to help address the problem of filter bubbles.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] In graph drawing, a **circular layout** is a style of drawing that places the vertices of a graph on a circle, often evenly spaced so that they form the vertices of a regular polygon.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] Circular layouts are a good fit for communications network topologies such as star or ring networks, and for the cyclic parts of metabolic networks.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] For graphs with a known Hamiltonian cycle, a circular layout allows the cycle to be depicted as the circle, and in this way circular layouts form the basis of the LCF notation for Hamiltonian cubic graphs.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] A circular layout may be used on its own for an entire graph drawing, but it also may be used as the layout for smaller clusters of vertices within a larger graph drawing, such as its biconnected components, clusters of genes in a gene interaction graph, or natural subgroups within a social network.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] If multiple vertex circles are used in this way, other methods such as force-directed graph drawing may be used to arrange the clusters.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] The edges of the drawing may be depicted as chords of the circle, as circular arcs (possibly perpendicular to the vertex circle, so that the edges model lines of the Poincaré disk model of hyperbolic geometry), or as other types of curve.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] The visual distinction between the inside and the outside of the vertex circle in a circular layout may be used to separate two different styles of edge drawing.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] For instance, a circular drawing algorithm of Gansner & Koren (2007) uses edge bundling within the circle, together with some edges that are not bundled, drawn outside the circle.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] For circular layouts of regular graphs, with edges drawn both inside and outside as circular arcs, the angle of incidence of one of these arcs with the vertex circle is the same at both ends of the arc, a property that simplifies the optimization of the angular resolution of the drawing.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] Several authors have studied the problem of finding a permutation of the vertices of a circular layout that minimizes the number of edge crossings when all edges are drawn inside the vertex circle.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] This number of crossings is zero only for outerplanar graphs.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] For other graphs, it may be optimized or reduced separately for each biconnected component of the graph before combining the solutions, as these components may be drawn so that they do not interact.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] In general, minimizing the number of crossings is NP-complete.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] (1995) described an approximation algorithm based on balanced cuts or edge separators, subsets of few edges whose removal disconnects the given graph into two subgraphs with approximately equal numbers of vertices.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] After finding an approximate cut, their algorithm arranges the two subgraphs on each side of the cut recursively, without considering the additional crossings formed by the edges that cross the cut.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] Their work cites a paper by Fan Chung and Shing-Tung Yau from 1994 that claimed $\rho =O(1)$ , but this was later found to have an erroneous proof.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] Instead, the best approximation known for the balanced cut problem has $\rho =O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ , giving this circular layout algorithm an approximation ratio of $O(\log ^{3}n)$ on graphs that have a large number of crossings relative to their vertex degrees.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] Heuristic methods for reducing the crossing complexity have also been devised, based e.g. on a careful vertex insertion order and on local optimization.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] A circular layout may also be used to maximize the number of crossings.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] In particular, choosing a random permutation for the vertices causes each possible crossing to occur with probability 1/3, so the expected number of crossings is within a factor of three of the maximum number of crossings among all possible layouts.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/circular-layout] Derandomizing this method gives a deterministic approximation algorithm with approximation ratio three.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] While graph drawing can be a difficult problem, force-directed algorithms, being physical simulations, usually require no special knowledge about graph theory such as planarity.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Force-directed graph drawing algorithms assign forces among the set of edges and the set of nodes of a graph drawing.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Typically, spring-like attractive forces based on Hooke's law are used to attract pairs of endpoints of the graph's edges towards each other, while simultaneously repulsive forces like those of electrically charged particles based on Coulomb's law are used to separate all pairs of nodes.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] In equilibrium states for this system of forces, the edges tend to have uniform length (because of the spring forces), and nodes that are not connected by an edge tend to be drawn further apart (because of the electrical repulsion).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Edge attraction and vertex repulsion forces may be defined using functions that are not based on the physical behavior of springs and particles; for instance, some force-directed systems use springs whose attractive force is logarithmic rather than linear.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] An alternative model considers a spring-like force for every pair of nodes $(i,j)$ where the ideal length $\delta _{ij}$ of each spring is proportional to the graph-theoretic distance between nodes *i* and *j*, without using a separate repulsive force.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Minimizing the difference (usually the squared difference) between Euclidean and ideal distances between nodes is then equivalent to a metric multidimensional scaling problem.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] A force-directed graph can involve forces other than mechanical springs and electrical repulsion.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Analogues of magnetic fields may be used for directed graphs.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Repulsive forces may be placed on edges as well as on nodes in order to avoid overlap or near-overlap in the final drawing.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] In drawings with curved edges such as circular arcs or spline curves, forces may also be placed on the control points of these curves, for instance to improve their angular resolution.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Once the forces on the nodes and edges of a graph have been defined, the behavior of the entire graph under these sources may then be simulated as if it were a physical system.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] In such a simulation, the forces are applied to the nodes, pulling them closer together or pushing them further apart.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] This is repeated iteratively until the system comes to a mechanical equilibrium state; i.e., their relative positions do not change anymore from one iteration to the next.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] The positions of the nodes in this equilibrium are used to generate a drawing of the graph.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] For forces defined from springs whose ideal length is proportional to the graph-theoretic distance, stress majorization gives a very well-behaved (i.e., monotonically convergent) and mathematically elegant way to minimize these differences and, hence, find a good layout for the graph.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] It is also possible to employ mechanisms that search more directly for energy minima, either instead of or in conjunction with physical simulation.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Such mechanisms, which are examples of general global optimization methods, include simulated annealing and genetic algorithms.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] At least for graphs of medium size (up to 50–500 vertices), the results obtained have usually very good quality based on the following criteria: uniform edge length, uniform vertex distribution and showing symmetry.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] This last criterion is among the most important ones and is hard to achieve with any other type of algorithm.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Force-directed algorithms can be easily adapted and extended to fulfill additional aesthetic criteria.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] This makes them the most versatile class of graph drawing algorithms.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] cluster graph drawing, constrained graph drawing, and dynamic graph drawing.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Since they are based on physical analogies of common objects, like springs, the behavior of the algorithms is relatively easy to predict and understand.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Typical force-directed algorithms are simple and can be implemented in a few lines of code.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Other classes of graph-drawing algorithms, like the ones for orthogonal layouts, are usually much more involved.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Another advantage of this class of algorithm is the interactive aspect.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] By drawing the intermediate stages of the graph, the user can follow how the graph evolves, seeing it unfold from a tangled mess into a good-looking configuration.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] In some interactive graph drawing tools, the user can pull one or more nodes out of their equilibrium state and watch them migrate back into position.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] force-directed algorithms often appear in the literature and in practice (because they are relatively easy to understand), more reasoned approaches are starting to gain traction.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] problems - so extremely mature approaches exist.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] approach to metric MDS can be applied to graph drawing as described above.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Monotonic convergence, the property that the algorithm will at each iteration decrease the stress or cost of the layout, is important because it guarantees that the layout will eventually reach a local minimum and stop.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Damping schedules cause the algorithm to stop, but cannot guarantee that a true local minimum is reached.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] is the number of nodes of the input graph.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] ), and in every iteration, all pairs of nodes need to be visited and their mutual repulsive forces computed.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] However, since repulsive forces are local in nature the graph can be partitioned such that only neighboring vertices are considered.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Force-directed algorithms, when combined with a graph clustering approach, can draw graphs of millions of nodes.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] The local minimum found can be, in many cases, considerably worse than a global minimum, which translates into a low-quality drawing.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] moves of the vertices, the final result can be strongly influenced by the initial layout, that in most cases is randomly generated.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] The problem of poor local minima becomes more important as the number of vertices of the graph increases.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] A combined application of different algorithms is helpful to solve this problem.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] to improve the placement of neighbouring nodes.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Another technique to achieve a global minimum is to use a multilevel approach.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Because of the simple nature of the forces in this case, the system cannot get stuck in local minima, but rather converges to a unique global optimum configuration.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] Because of this work, embeddings of planar graphs with convex faces are sometimes called Tutte embeddings.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] The combination of attractive forces on adjacent vertices, and repulsive forces on all vertices, was first used by Eades (1984); additional pioneering work on this type of force-directed layout was done by Fruchterman & Reingold (1991).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/force-directed-graph-drawing] The idea of using only spring forces between all pairs of vertices, with ideal spring lengths equal to the vertices' graph-theoretic distance, is from Kamada & Kawai (1989).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] The ideal form for a layered drawing would be an upward planar drawing, in which all edges are oriented in a consistent direction and no pairs of edges cross.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] In its simplest form, layered graph drawing algorithms may require O(*mn*) time in graphs with *n* vertices and *m* edges, because of the large number of dummy vertices that may be created.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] However, for some variants of the algorithm, it is possible to simulate the effect of the dummy vertices without actually constructing them explicitly, leading to a near-linear time implementation.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] The "dot" tool in Graphviz produces layered drawings.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] A layered graph drawing algorithm is also included in Microsoft Automatic Graph Layout and in Tulip.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] Although typically drawn with vertices in rows and edges proceeding from top to bottom, layered graph drawing algorithms may instead be drawn with vertices in columns and edges proceeding from left to right.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] The same algorithmic framework has also been applied to radial layouts in which the graphs are arranged in concentric circles around some starting node and to three-dimensional layered drawings of graphs.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] In layered graph drawings with many long edges, edge clutter may be reduced by grouping sets of edges into bundles and routing them together through the same set of dummy vertices.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] Similarly, for drawings with many edges crossing between pairs of consecutive layers, the edges in maximal bipartite subgraphs may be grouped into confluent bundles.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] Drawings in which the vertices are arranged in layers may be constructed by algorithms that do not follow Sugiyama's framework.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] For instance, it is possible to tell whether an undirected graph has a drawing with at most *k* crossings, using *h* layers, in an amount of time that is polynomial for any fixed choice of *k* and *h*, using the fact that the graphs that have drawings of this type have bounded pathwidth.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] For layered drawings of concept lattices, a hybrid approach combining Sugiyama's framework with additive methods (in which each vertex represents a set and the position of the vertex is a sum of vectors representing elements in the set) may be used.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] In this hybrid approach, the vertex permutation and coordinate assignment phases of the algorithm are replaced by a single phase in which the horizontal position of each vertex is chosen as a sum of scalars representing the elements for that vertex.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/layered-graph-drawing] Layered graph drawing methods have also been used to provide an initial placement for force-directed graph drawing algorithms.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] A **radial tree**, or **radial map**, is a method of displaying a tree structure (e.g., a tree data structure) in a way that expands outwards, radially.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] It is one of many ways to visually display a tree, with examples dating back to the early 20th century.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] In use, it is a type of information graphic.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] The overall distance "d" is the distance between levels of the graph.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] It is chosen so that the overall layout will fit within a screen.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] Layouts are generated by working outward from the center, root.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] The first level is a special case because all the nodes have the same parent.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] The nodes for level 1 can be distributed evenly, or weighted depending on the number of children they have.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] For subsequent levels, the children are positioned within sectors of the remaining space, so that child nodes of one parent do not overlap with others.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] There are many extensions to this algorithm to create more visually balanced layouts, to allow users to navigate from node to node (changing the center), or accommodate node labels and combine force-directed layouts with radial layouts.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] The layout has some similarities to a hyperbolic tree, though a key difference is that hyperbolic trees are based on hyperbolic geometry, whereas in a radial tree the distance between orbits is relatively linear.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] In a simple case, the first node is at the top, and the linked nodes are beneath.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] As each node typically has more than one child, the resulting shape is relatively triangular.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] In a radial layout, instead of each successive generation being displayed a row below, each generation is displayed in a new, outer orbit.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] Since the length of each orbit increases with the radius, there tends to be more room for the nodes.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] A radial tree will spread the larger number of nodes over a larger area as the levels increase.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] We use the terms level and depth interchangeably.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/radial-tree] Nevertheless, the number of nodes increases exponentially with the distance from the first node, whereas the circumference of each orbit increases linearly, so, by the outer orbits, the nodes tend to be packed together.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **tree** is an undirected graph in which every pair of distinct vertices is connected by *exactly one* path, or equivalently, a connected acyclic undirected graph.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A **forest** is an undirected graph in which any two vertices are connected by *at most one* path, or equivalently an acyclic undirected graph, or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A directed tree, oriented tree, polytree, or singly connected network is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A polyforest (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The various kinds of data structures referred to as trees in computer science have underlying graphs that are trees in graph theory, although such data structures are generally rooted trees.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree may be directed, called a directed rooted tree, either making all its edges point away from the root—in which case it is called an arborescence or out-tree—or making all its edges point towards the root—in which case it is called an anti-arborescence or in-tree.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree itself has been defined by some authors as a directed graph.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A rooted forest is a disjoint union of rooted trees.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The term *tree* was coined in 1857 by the British mathematician Arthur Cayley.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] It may, however, be considered as a forest consisting of zero trees.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* (or inner vertex) is a vertex of degree at least 2.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Similarly, an *external vertex* (or outer vertex, terminal vertex or leaf) is a vertex of degree 1.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A branch vertex in a tree is a vertex of degree at least 3.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] An *irreducible tree* (or series-reduced tree) is a tree in which there is no vertex of degree 2 (enumerated at sequence A000014 in the OEIS).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *forest* is an undirected acyclic graph or equivalently a disjoint union of trees.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Trivially so, each connected component of a forest is a tree.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] As special cases, the order-zero graph (a forest consisting of zero trees), a single tree, and an edgeless graph, are examples of forests.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Since for every tree *V* − *E* = 1, we can easily count the number of trees that are within a forest by subtracting the difference between total vertices and total edges.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] *V* − *E* = number of trees in a forest.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *polytree* (or *directed tree* or *oriented tree* or *singly connected network*) is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is both connected and acyclic.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Some authors restrict the phrase "directed tree" to the case where the edges are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see arborescence).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *polyforest* (or directed forest or oriented forest) is a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a forest.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] In other words, if we replace its directed edges with undirected edges, we obtain an undirected graph that is acyclic.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] As with directed trees, some authors restrict the phrase "directed forest" to the case where the edges of each connected component are all directed towards a particular vertex, or all directed away from a particular vertex (see branching).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *rooted tree* is a tree in which one vertex has been designated the root.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The edges of a rooted tree can be assigned a natural orientation, either away from or towards the root, in which case the structure becomes a directed rooted tree.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] When a directed rooted tree has an orientation away from the root, it is called an *arborescence* or *out-tree*; when it has an orientation towards the root, it is called an *anti-arborescence* or *in-tree*.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The tree-order is the partial ordering on the vertices of a tree with *u* < *v* only if the unique path from the root to v passes through u.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A rooted tree T that is a subgraph of some graph G is a normal tree if the ends of every T-path in G are comparable in this tree-order (Diestel 2005, p.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Rooted trees, often with an additional structure such as an ordering of the neighbors at each vertex, are a key data structure in computer science; see tree data structure.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] In a context where trees typically have a root, a tree without any designated root is called a *free tree*.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *labeled tree* is a tree in which each vertex is given a unique label.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The vertices of a labeled tree on n vertices (for nonnegative integers n) are typically given the labels 1, 2, …, *n*.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *recursive tree* is a labeled rooted tree where the vertex labels respect the tree order (i.e., if *u* < *v* for two vertices u and v, then the label of u is smaller than the label of v).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] In a rooted tree, the **parent** of a vertex v is the vertex connected to v on the path to the root; every vertex has a unique parent, except the root has no parent.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *child* of a vertex v is a vertex of which v is the parent.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] An *ascendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either the parent of v or is (recursively) an ascendant of a parent of v.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *descendant* of a vertex v is any vertex that is either a child of v or is (recursively) a descendant of a child of v.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *sibling* to a vertex v is any other vertex on the tree that shares a parent with v.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] An *internal vertex* is a vertex that is not a leaf.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of a vertex in a rooted tree is the length of the longest downward path to a leaf from that vertex.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The *height* of the tree is the height of the root.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The *depth* of a vertex is the length of the path to its root (*root path*).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The depth of a tree is the maximum depth of any vertex.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Depth is commonly needed in the manipulation of the various self-balancing trees, AVL trees in particular.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] The root has depth zero, leaves have height zero, and a tree with only a single vertex (hence both a root and leaf) has depth and height zero.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Conventionally, an empty tree (a tree with no vertices, if such are allowed) has depth and height −1.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A *k-ary tree* (for nonnegative integers k) is a rooted tree in which each vertex has at most k children.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] 2-ary trees are often called *binary trees*, while 3-ary trees are sometimes called *ternary trees*.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] An *ordered tree* (alternatively, *plane tree* or *positional tree*) is a rooted tree in which an ordering is specified for the children of each vertex.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] This is called a "plane tree" because an ordering of the children is equivalent to an embedding of the tree in the plane, with the root at the top and the children of each vertex lower than that vertex.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Given an embedding of a rooted tree in the plane, if one fixes a direction of children, say left to right, then an embedding gives an ordering of the children.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Conversely, given an ordered tree, and conventionally drawing the root at the top, then the child vertices in an ordered tree can be drawn left-to-right, yielding an essentially unique planar embedding.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Cayley's formula states that there are *n**n*−2 trees on n labeled vertices.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] A more general problem is to count spanning trees in an undirected graph, which is addressed by the matrix tree theorem.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] (Cayley's formula is the special case of spanning trees in a complete graph.) The similar problem of counting all the subtrees regardless of size is #P-complete in the general case (Jerrum (1994)).
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] Counting the number of unlabeled free trees is a harder problem.
[src:hierarchical-edge-bundling/tree-graph-theory] No closed formula for the number *t*(*n*) of trees with n vertices up to graph isomorphism is known.
